              <fr:year>2024</fr:year>
              <fr:month>9</fr:month>
              <fr:day>6</fr:day>
            </fr:date>
            <fr:uri>https://trebor-huang.github.io/forest/algm-0022/</fr:uri>
            <fr:display-uri>algm-0022</fr:display-uri>
            <fr:route>/forest/algm-0022/</fr:route>
            <fr:title text="dense subsite of affine opens">dense subsite of affine opens</fr:title>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <html:p>
  Given a <fr:link href="/forest/algm-000R/" title="scheme" uri="https://trebor-huang.github.io/forest/algm-000R/" display-uri="algm-000R" type="local">scheme</fr:link> <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[S]]></fr:tex>, the underlying locale (equipped with the canonical coverage) has a <fr:link href="/forest/algm-0021/" title="dense subsite" uri="https://trebor-huang.github.io/forest/algm-0021/" display-uri="algm-0021" type="local">dense subsite</fr:link> whose objects are affine opens, and morphisms are distinguished open subspaces. Note that this isn’t a full subcategory, since <fr:link href="/forest/algm-0020/" title="a non-distinguished affine subscheme" uri="https://trebor-huang.github.io/forest/algm-0020/" display-uri="algm-0020" type="local">there exist affine open subspaces that are not distinguished</fr:link>.
</html:p>
            <html:p>
  Since schemes are covered by affine schemes, and distinguished opens form a basis in the <fr:link href="/forest/algm-0007/" title="localic spectrum of a commutative ring" uri="https://trebor-huang.github.io/forest/algm-0007/" display-uri="algm-0007" type="local">localic spectrum of a commutative ring</fr:link>, every open in <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[S]]></fr:tex> is covered by affine opens. On the other hand, <fr:link href="/forest/algm-0016/" title="Nike’s trick" uri="https://trebor-huang.github.io/forest/algm-0016/" display-uri="algm-0016" type="local">Nike’s trick</fr:link> guarantees the condition on morphisms for dense subsites.
</html:p>
          </fr:mainmatter>
        </fr:tree>
        <fr:tree show-metadata="true" expanded="false" toc="false" numbered="false">
          <fr:frontmatter>
            <fr:authors>
              <fr:author>
                <fr:link href="/forest/trebor/" title="Trebor" uri="https://trebor-huang.github.io/forest/trebor/" display-uri="trebor" type="local">Trebor</fr:link>
              </fr:author>
            </fr:authors>
            <fr:date>
              <fr:year>2024</fr:year>
              <fr:month>8</fr:month>
              <fr:day>22</fr:day>
            </fr:date>
            <fr:uri>https://trebor-huang.github.io/forest/algm-001Y/</fr:uri>
            <fr:display-uri>algm-001Y</fr:display-uri>
            <fr:route>/forest/algm-001Y/</fr:route>
            <fr:title text="affinification">affinification</fr:title>
            <fr:taxon>Definition</fr:taxon>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <html:p>
  Given a <fr:link href="/forest/algm-000R/" title="scheme" uri="https://trebor-huang.github.io/forest/algm-000R/" display-uri="algm-000R" type="local">scheme</fr:link> <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[S]]></fr:tex>, we can produce a best <fr:link href="/forest/algm-000Q/" title="affine scheme" uri="https://trebor-huang.github.io/forest/algm-000Q/" display-uri="algm-000Q" type="local">affine</fr:link> approximation <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[S \to  S']]></fr:tex> for it. This serves as the adjoint unit of the <fr:link href="/forest/algm-0014/" title="adjunction of global section and \operatorname {Spec}" uri="https://trebor-huang.github.io/forest/algm-0014/" display-uri="algm-0014" type="local">adjunction of global section and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\operatorname {Spec}]]></fr:tex></fr:link>. Here we give a construction from the ground up.
</html:p>
            <html:p>
  We define <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[S' = \operatorname {Spec} \Gamma (\top , \mathscr {O}_X)]]></fr:tex>. For the map <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[S \to  S']]></fr:tex>, we define the preimage of the distinguished open <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[D(f)]]></fr:tex> to be the non-vanishing open of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f \in  \Gamma (\top , \mathscr {O}_X)]]></fr:tex>, which is defined on each affine subscheme as the distinguished open of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f]]></fr:tex>. This is obviously continuous. We can then pull back a section <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f/g]]></fr:tex> by considering them as an element of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\Gamma (\top , \mathscr {O}_X)]]></fr:tex> and restricting them.
</html:p>
            <html:p>
  A scheme is affine iff the affinification is an isomorphism. This is a formal consequence that affine schemes form a full subcategory of schemes.
</html:p>
          </fr:mainmatter>
        </fr:tree>
        <fr:tree show-metadata="true" expanded="false" toc="false" numbered="false">
          <fr:frontmatter>
            <fr:authors>
              <fr:author>
                <fr:link href="/forest/trebor/" title="Trebor" uri="https://trebor-huang.github.io/forest/trebor/" display-uri="trebor" type="local">Trebor</fr:link>
